*Snehadrita  here! Hope you’re doing well!*

 *Entrepreneurship Cell, IIT Bombay* is back with its Campus Ambassador Internship Program for the session 2022-23. 

 

About E-Cell, IIT Bombay- E-Cell, IIT Bombay is Asia's largest student-run entrepreneurship body having received patronages from UNESCO, Make in India, Startup India, and Digital India for our contribution to promoting entrepreneurship. Since its inception in 1998, E-Cell has undertaken various initiatives to support the emerging Indian startup ecosystem. Keeping our motto in mind, E-Cell, IIT Bombay reaches out to all the colleges across India to promote entrepreneurial outlook among students by engaging them with different activities of the E-Cell, IIT Bombay. Every year more than 7k+ participants register for the College Ambassador program. Out of which, around 2000 students from 2500+ colleges are selected as our Campus Ambassador.

 

The selected Campus Ambassador, in his/her entire tenure, would represent E-Cell, IIT Bombay in their college and would be equipped with tools that would be aimed to bring about his personal development as well as the advancement of the entrepreneurial ecosystem in his college.

 

Perks and Benefits of Campus Ambassador Internship Program:

Get a certificate of appreciation from The Entrepreneurship Cell, IIT Bombay 

Chance to visit IIT Bombay: Explore E-Summit 2023, The Annual Flagship event of E-Cell IIT Bombay.

FREE Tech Workshops worth INR 7.5 lakhs by Industry Experts

140+ Internship Opportunities to top CAs from India Accelerator, SkillEnable, FORTYTWO LABS and GetWork

Prizes worth INR 8 Lakhs which includes courses, vouchers, coupons, merchandise and subscription.

 

Q1. Who can join the program?

A1. Students from any college, stream, year of college can register for the Campus Ambassador Program.

 

Q2. Is there any interview/ selection process?

A2. No, there will be no interview process, you will be selected on the basis of your response.

 

You can register for the program here: https://bit.ly/3QEbKa3 

 

Added Incentive: 


Register yourself and spread the word to your friends and connections in different colleges about the program and get a chance to get exciting incentives.

 
If you have any questions or queries feel free to contact me any time.

8/17/22, 14:47 - +91 89108 12276: Eigenvalues are the special set of scalars associated with the system of linear equations. It is mostly used in matrix equations. ‘Eigen’ is a German word that means ‘proper’ or ‘characteristic’. Therefore, the term eigenvalue can be termed as characteristic value, characteristic root, proper values or latent roots as well. In simple words, the eigenvalue is a scalar that is used to transform the eigenvector. The basic equation is
Ax = λx
The number or scalar value “λ” is an eigenvalue of A.

9/14/22, 22:35 - Saif: Merge sort krna hai na ?
9/14/22, 22:36 - Rounak Sen Aot: na
9/14/22, 22:36 - Ishani Roy (AOT): Modified Bubble
9/14/22, 22:37 - Rounak Sen Aot: void bubble(int a[], int n){
	for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
		int swaps=0;
		for(int j=0; j<n-i-1; j++){
			if(a[j]>a[j+1]){
				int t=a[j];
				a[j]=a[j+1];
				a[j+1]=t;
				swaps++;
			}
		}
		if(swaps==0)
			break;
	}
}

8/26/23, 12:04 - Rousseau Chowdhury: *Coding guidelines:*
1. All the programs should be properly indented.
2. Comment lines must be included to increase the understandibility of the program.
3. All identifiers should be meaningful and properly named. 
4. Maintain coupling and cohesion.
5. The same name for different variables should be avoided. 
6. Global variables should be avoided.

11/6/23, 20:36 - Rounak Sen Aot: All of the answer choices are important steps in scheduling a project.

Here is a brief explanation of each step:

Break down each activity into tasks: This is the process of decomposing the project into smaller and smaller tasks. This helps to make the project more manageable and to identify the dependencies between tasks.
Determine the dependencies among different tasks: This involves identifying which tasks must be completed before other tasks can begin. This information is used to create a schedule that shows the order in which tasks must be completed.
Establish the time estimates for each task: This involves estimating how long each task will take to complete. This information is used to create a schedule that shows the start and finish dates for each task.
Represent the activities to show the flow information within the system: This involves creating a visual representation of the project schedule, such as a Gantt chart. This helps to communicate the schedule to the project team and to identify any potential bottlenecks.
All of these steps are important in scheduling a project effectively. By following these steps, project managers can create a schedule that will help them to complete the project on time and within budget.

Therefore, the best answer is All of these.

3/14/24, 14:03 - Soumyajit: **Rules and Regulations of UXopia 🎨**

1. Each room will be provided with an application topic and key information about it. Participants must craft their designs based on this information.

2. Designing must be done exclusively using Figma; no other design tools are permitted. 🚫

3. Participants will have 1 hour and 30 minutes to complete their designs. ⏱️

4. The competition consists of two rounds. In the first round, the top two designing groups from each room will advance to the final round. 🏆

5. The final round will include exciting twists beyond just designing the applications. 🔄

6. It is mandatory for each participant to bring a laptop, with at least one laptop per group required. 💻

7. In the final round, the top three groups will be selected, and they will receive thrilling and innovative gifts as prizes. 🎁

**Most Important:**

1. Participants are strictly prohibited from using any AI tools; any violation will result in disqualification. ❌

2. Only Figma is allowed for designing; no other tools will be accepted. 🛠️

Join us at UXopia, where creativity meets competition! 🌟✨

4/24/24, 00:34 - Sourish(AOT): After about 400+ messages amar ektai question ache jara eii attendance niye lafalafi korchs tara 100% attendence niye korbi ta kii bolto
Naa toh college theke 100% er certificate deii je show off korbi or kichu it's just a criteria exams e boste dewar.
R jara eto jhamela korchs eke besi oke kom attendance niye tader kii eii besi attendance er jnne number besi pabi kii seta bll.
R kom attendance thakle class attend korte lage bari bose thakle konodino attendance barbe naa 😪😪
Lastly, ektai kotha vebe dekhis keu jodi repeat e pore jaai r se exams dite naa pare ete kar e ba valo hobe nijera vebe dekhis (if you have that humanity in yourself) je ekta friend exams dite na parle tar 1ta year nosto hote dekhte....ultimately nijerder e toh batchmate

Er por kichu bachal che torko korte je mar attendence besi taai esob bolchi n all tora boltei paris but amar tate kichu jaai ase jaai na

4/24/24, 11:36 - Arya: #include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <stdbool.h>
#include <limits.h>

#define MAX_VERTICES 100
#define MAX_EDGES 100

struct Edge {
    int source, destination, weight;
};

struct Graph {
    int V, E;
    struct Edge edges[MAX_EDGES];
};

void initializeGraph(struct Graph* graph, int V, int E) {
    graph->V = V;
    graph->E = E;
}

void initializeSingleSource(int V, int source, int distance[]) {
    for (int i = 0; i < V; i++) {
        distance[i] = (i == source) ? 0 : INT_MAX;
    }
}

void relax(int u, int v, int w, int* distance) {
    if (distance[u] != INT_MAX && distance[u] + w < distance[v]) {
        distance[v] = distance[u] + w;
    }
}

bool bellmanFord(struct Graph* graph, int source) {
    int V = graph->V;
    int E = graph->E;
    int distance[MAX_VERTICES];

    initializeSingleSource(V, source, distance);

    for (int i = 1; i <= V - 1; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < E; j++) {
            int u = graph->edges[j].source;
            int v = graph->edges[j].destination;
            int weight = graph->edges[j].weight;
            relax(u, v, weight, distance);
        }
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < E; i++) {
        int u = graph->edges[i].source;
        int v = graph->edges[i].destination;
        int weight = graph->edges[i].weight;
        if (distance[u] != INT_MAX && distance[u] + weight < distance[v]) {
            return false; // Negative weight cycle detected
        }
    }

    return true;
}

int main() {
    struct Graph graph;
    int V, E, source;
    printf("Enter the number of vertices and edges: ");
    scanf("%d %d", &V, &E);

    initializeGraph(&graph, V, E);

    printf("Enter the source vertex: ");
    scanf("%d", &source);

    printf("Enter the edges in format (source destination weight):\n");
    for (int i = 0; i < E; i++) {
        scanf("%d %d %d", &graph.edges[i].source, &graph.edges[i].destination, &graph.edges[i].weight);
    }

    if (bellmanFord(&graph, source)) {
        printf("No negative weight cycle detected.\n");
        printf("Vertex\tDistance from source\n");
        for (int i = 0; i < V; i++) 
        {
            printf("%d\t%d\n", i, graph.edges[i].weight);
        }
    } else {
        printf("Graph contains negative weight cycle.\n");
    }

    return 0;
}

4/24/24, 11:50 - Raja (AOT): ```
#!/bin/bash

echo -n "Enter a string: "
read s

temp=$s
revstr=""
len=$(echo -n $s | wc -c)

for ((i = len; i >= 1; i--)); do
	revstr="$revstr$(echo $temp | cut -c $i)"
	echo $revstr
done

if [ "$revstr" = "$s" ]; then
	echo "Palin"
else
	echo "Not Palin"
fi

#!/bin/bash

echo -n "Enter a string: "
read s

u2l=$(echo $s | tr [:lower:] [:upper:])
echo $u2l

vowels=$(echo $u2l | tr -cd "AEIOU")
echo $vowels

special_less=$(echo $s | tr -d [:alnum:])
echo $special_less

4/29/24, 19:34 - Rousseau Chowdhury: Dear Sir,
 We hope this mail finds you in good health and fortune. We the students of 6th semester were asked to submit our necessary documents and details to the corporate relations department by 29th April, 2024. But no time was mentioned there. 
 This database is important not just for us but for the college as well. And this is the very reason why many students chose to take their time to check and recheck the informations they were providing. 
 Some of the students had received an incomplete result in the 5th semester University exams and they didn't submit the form because they were waiting and hoping for this incomplete status to be updated. 
 We understand, that submitting forms as important as these at the eleventh hour can indeed be termed as a little irresponsible. But most of the students waited because there was no time mentioned and they wanted to cross check the informations they were providing.
 We request you to look into this matter and take a decision and oblige. 
                                      Thanking you,
                                      Your faithfully 
                         Students of 6th semester CSBS

5/1/24, 19:39 - Anish (AOT): Subject: Request to Suspend Offline Classes Due to Heat

Dear Sir,

I hope this email finds you well. We, the students of Academy of Technology, are concerned about the impact of the current heatwave on our health and learning.

The soaring temperatures make it challenging for us to focus during offline classes, posing health risks and hindering effective learning.

We kindly request your support in temporarily suspending offline classes until the heatwave subsides. Prioritizing our safety and ensuring a conducive learning environment is crucial.

We suggest exploring remote learning options to maintain academic progress during this time.

Thank you for considering our request. Your prompt action would be greatly appreciated.

Warm regards,

Renaissance = Rebirth, as they will be wearing the new hat of a professional after completing the graduation

Vigama (sanskrit) = farewell, 

Valete/Vale (Archaic English) = farewell with excitement, joy, sorrow, 

Convene (English) = come or bring together for a meeting or activity

6/25/24, 23:40 - Adisita: eta solve korar jnno duto transformation lagbe ekta hcche rotate by 45° and another is scale the square in x direction by 2 units and in y direction 3 units 
so basically start with the initial coordinates of the square A(1,0) B ... c... d.. ja ja dewa ache 
first hcche rotate 
Rotate matrix for clockwise rotation by an angle theta is R (theta) = (cos theta  sin theta 
              -sin theta   cos theta)
ebar theta er jagay 45° bosiye sin cos er value gulo likhe solve krbi
